description: From French déboucher (de + bouche (“mouth”)), modelled on Italian sboccare.

entries.meaning: (geography) A narrow outlet from which a body of water pours.
examples: In level portions of the country vertical shafts are preferred, but where the mine is situated upon a hill a debouch may often be found below the sulphur seam, ...

entries.meaning: (military) A fortress at the end of a defile.

verbs.description: debouch (third-person singular simple present debouches, present participle debouching, simple past and past participle debouched)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To pour forth from a narrow opening; to emerge from a narrow place like a defile into open country or a wider space.
